o;ll get the £13.40 rate for each of them.</p>\n\n<h2>How Child Benefit is paid</h2>\n<p>Child Benefit is paid into your <a href=\"/how-to-have-your-benefits-paid\" title=\"how to have your benefits paid\">bank account</a> every 4 weeks. You can get it paid weekly if you&rsquo;re a single parent or getting certain other benefits, eg Income Support. </p>\n\n<p>When you get paid depends on where you live. You can <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/tools/childbenefit/chbcalc.htm\" title=\"find your next Child Benefit payment date\">find your next payment date</a> online.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>From April 2013 a limit will be put on the total amount of benefit that most people aged 16 to 64 can get. This is called a <a href=\"/benefit-cap\" title=\"benefit cap\">benefit cap</a>.</p>\n</div>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/child-benefit/eligibility","slug":"eligibility","order":3,"title":"Eligibility","body":"\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>Only one person can get Child Benefit for a child.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>You normally qualify for Child Benefit if you&rsquo;re responsible for a child under 16 (or under 20 if they stay in approved <a href=\"/child-benefit-16-19\" title=\"Child Benefit if for 16-19 year olds in education or training\">education or training</a>) and you live in the UK.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>Child Benefit <a href=\"/child-benefit-16-19/child-benefit-extensions\" title=\"Child Benefit extension\">continues for 20 weeks</a> if 16 or 17 year olds leave education or training and register with the armed services or a government sponsored careers service.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>Eligibility rules are different if your child:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><a href=\"/child-benefit-child-into-care\" title=\"Child Benefit if your child goes into care\">goes into care</a></li>\n  <li><a href=\"/child-benefit-hospital-residential-care\" title=\"Child Benefit if your child goes into hospital or residential care\">goes into hospital or residential care</a></li>\n  <li><a href=\"/child-benefit-child-lives-with-someone-else\" title=\"Child Benefit if your child lives with someone else\">lives with someone else</a></li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Adoptions and fostering</h2>\n<p>If you&rsquo;re adopting a child, apply for Child Benefit as soon as the child comes to live with you - you don&rsquo;t have to wait until the adoption process is complete. </p>\n\n<p>The nationality of the child doesn&rsquo;t affect whether you&rsquo;re entitled to Child Benefit or not.</p>\n\n<p>You might be able to get Child Benefit for a period before the adoption - <a rel=\"external\" href=\"https://directgov-online.hmrc.gov.uk/shortforms/form/CBO_Specific?dept-name=CBO&amp;sub-dept-name=General&amp;location=3&amp;origin=http://www.hmrc.gov.uk&amp;lang=eng\" title=\"Email the Child Benefit Office\">contact the Child Benefit Office</a> to find out.</p>\n\n<p>If you foster a child, you&rsquo;ll get Child Benefit if the local council isn&rsquo;t paying anything towards the child&rsquo;s accommodation or maintenance.</p>\n\n<h2>Looking after someone else&rsquo;s child</h2>\n\n<p>You may be able to get Child Benefit if you&rsquo;ve got an informal arrangement to look after a friend or relative&rsquo;s child. </p>\n\n<p>If your local council is paying towards the child&rsquo;s accommodation or maintenance you might not qualify - <a rel=\"external\" href=\"https://directgov-online.hmrc.gov.uk/shortforms/form/CBO_Specific?dept-name=CBO&amp;sub-dept-name=General&amp;location=3&amp;origin=http://www.hmrc.gov.uk&amp;lang=eng\" title=\"Email the Child Benefit Office\">contact the Child Benefit Office</a> to find out.</p>\n\n<p>If you want to make a claim, you need to try to agree with the person who is currently getting Child Benefit (eg the parent) that you can make a claim instead - 2 people can&rsquo;t get Child Benefit for the same child.</p>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re responsible for a child who has lost one or both of their parents, you may also be entitled to <a href=\"/guardians-allowance\" title=\"Guardian's Allowance\">Guardian&rsquo;s Allowance</a>. </p>\n\n<h2>Living abroad</h2>\n<p>You could get Child Benefit if you&rsquo;re a national of an <abbr title=\"European Economic Area\">EEA</abbr> country or Switzerland, and work in the UK (or get certain UK benefits, eg State Pension).</p>\n\n<p>There&rsquo;s more information about <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/childbenefit/start/who-qualifies/live-work-abroad.htm\" title=\"Child Benefit if you're living or working abroad\">Child Benefit if you&rsquo;re living or working abroad</a> on the HM Revenue &amp; Customs (<abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>) website.</p>\n\n<h2>New arrivals to the UK</h2>\n<p>You could get Child Benefit if your main home is now in the UK and you have permission to enter the UK and stay there - there&rsquo;s more information about this on the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/childbenefit/start/who-qualifies/new-arrivals-uk.htm\" title=\"Child Benefit and new arrivals to the UK\"><abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> website.</a></p>\n\n<h2>Questions about eligibility</h2>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re not sure about your eligibility, contact the Child Benefit Office.</p>\n\n<div class=\"contact\">\n<p><strong>Child Benefit Helpline</strong><br />\n<a href=\"https://directgov-online.hmrc.gov.uk/shortforms/form/CBO_Specific?dept-name=CBO&amp;sub-dept-name=General&amp;location=3&amp;origin=http://www.hmrc.gov.uk&amp;lang=eng\" title=\"Email the Child Benefit Office\" rel=\"external\">Enquiry form</a> <br />\n<strong>Telephone:</strong> 08453 021 444<br />\n<strong>Textphone:</strong> 08453 021 474  <br />\nMonday to Friday, 8am to 8pm<br />\nSaturday, 8am to 4pm</p>\n</div>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/child-benefit/how-to-claim","slug":"how-to-claim","order":4,"title":"How to claim","body":"<ol class=\"steps\">\n<li><p>Fill in a <a href=\"http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/forms/ch2-online-stubb.htm\" title=\"Child Benefit claim form\" rel=\"external\">Child Benefit claim form.</a></p>\n</li>\n<li><p>Send it to the Child Benefit Office with your child’s original birth or adoption certificate.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<div class=\"address\"><div class=\"adr org fn\"><p>\n\nChild Benefit Office (Washington)\n<br />Freepost\n<br />NEA 10463\n<br />PO Box 133\n<br />Washington NE38 7BR\n<br />\n</p></div></div>\n\n<p>The claim form is also available in Welsh.</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/forms/ch2-welsh.pdf\" title=\"Download 'Child Benefit claim form - Welsh version' (PDF, 120KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Child Benefit claim form - Welsh version’ (PDF, 120KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<p>Claim Child Benefit as soon as your child is born or comes to live with you.</p>\n\n<p>Child Benefit can only be backdated for 3 months - make your claim as soon as possible.</p>\n\n<p>If you don&rsquo;t have the birth or adoption certificate, you should still send in your claim form - send the certificate later on when you&rsquo;ve got it.</p>\n\n<p>You don&rsquo;t need the birth or adoption certificate if you&rsquo;ve claimed Child Benefit before and are making a new claim for the same child.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>If you’ve lost the birth or adoption certificate you can <a href=\"/order-copy-birth-death-marriage-certificate\" title=\"order a new birth or adoption certificate\">order a new one</a>.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Claiming Child Benefit for someone else</h2>\n<p>In certain circumstances you can <a href=\"/claim-child-benefit-behalf-someone-else\" title=\"Claim Child Benefit on behalf of someone else\">manage someone else&rsquo;s Child Benefit claim.</a></p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/child-benefit/further-information","slug":"further-information","order":5,"title":"Further information","body":"<h2>Child Benefit number</h2>\n<p>You can <a href=\"/child-benefit-number\" title=\"Finding your Child Benefit number\">find your Child Benefit number</a> on any paperwork you have from the Child Benefit Office.</p>\n\n<p>You should keep your paperwork until you stop getting Child Benefit.</p>\n\n<h2>Other benefits</h2>\n\n<p>Child Benefit doesn&rsquo;t count as income for other benefits. </p>\n\n<p>If you get Housing Benefit or Council Tax Benefit, the office paying you needs to know if you start or stop getting Child Benefit. This is so they can work out how much to pay you.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>You might be able to get other benefits too, eg <a href=\"/child-tax-credit/overview\" title=\"Child Tax Credit\">Child Tax Credit</a> - use the <a href=\"/benefits-adviser\" title=\"benefits adviser\">benefits adviser tool</a> to find out what you could get.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Child Benefit and your State Pension</h2>\n\n<p>If your child is under 12 and you&rsquo;re not working or don&rsquo;t earn enough to pay National Insurance contributions, Child Benefit can help you qualify for <a href=\"/boost-state-pension/overview\" title=\"National Insurance credits\">National Insurance credits</a>.</p>\n\n<p>These credits count towards your <a href=\"/state-pension\" title=\"State Pension\">State Pension</a>. They protect it by making sure you don&rsquo;t have gaps in your National Insurance record.</p>\n\n<h3>If you were getting Child Benefit before 6 April 2010</h3>\n\n<p>If you were getting Child Benefit for a child under 16, you would have automatically qualified for Home Responsibilities Protection instead - this counts towards your State Pension in the same way.</p>\n\n<p>If you were getting Child Benefit for a child under 6, you would have automatically built up entitlement to an extra pension through the Second State Pension.</p>\n\n<h2>Changes of circumstances</h2>\n<p>You must report any changes to your family life (eg getting married) or to your child&